Q1 (06/17/2020): For soft soil simulation would a simple terramechanics solution be acceptable, or do you also need a complex terramechanics capability?
A: This STTR topic is aimed at the needs of the broader, diverse market , not necessarily at one particular customer.&nbsp; As such, modeling capability that can accommodate more diverse soil types within a broad range of permeability, saturation, heterogeneity, etc is likely to be more broadly useful. It should be a goal to design the simulator framework such that it may accept improved (more accurate, increasingly higher fidelity, faster, etc) solutions over time.

Q2 (06/17/2020): Can one or several of the sub-modules of the proposed solution be proprietary as long as the main module that links all the sub-modules together is open source?
A: <p class="MsoPlainText">If the software components were either developed at private expense or developed using STTR funding, then my understanding is they would be protected by the applicable rights. The STTR data rights would only apply to those specific components developed/enhanced through performance funded by the STTR funding.

Q3 (05/28/2020): Is a modular approach that pulls in pre-existing simulation environments (assuming they are open source) acceptable? These might be written in different programming languages.
A: <span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:#1F497D;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">It is a good feature to allow the proposed simulator to import pre-existing simulation environments.&nbsp; However, the simulator should come with a viable user-friendly open source means to build, configure, and position items in the simulated environment. </span>

Q4 (05/28/2020): Are there any requirements constraints on architecture? (e.g. programming language, operating system)
A: <span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:#1F497D;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">The STTR topic description indicates the software should conform to open source standards and provide compatibility with ROS.&nbsp;&nbsp; The software should operate on common operating systems linux/Ubuntu and Windows.</span>

Q5 (05/28/2020): The requested software covers an extremely wide range of domains. Of the simulation domains mentioned (sensing, vehicle dynamics, terramechanics, communications) is there a domain and/or sub-domain (e.g. camera sensing, wheel/soft-earth dynamics) that you feel is particularly important or lacking in currently available tools?
A: <span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:#1F497D;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">As your question suggests, simulations that have all of these combined attributes is a particular attribute that is lacking.&nbsp; For example, it is very difficult to find a simulator that has both very good photorealistic visualization that allows vision-based perception training and very good physics/contact models for manipulation and other physical interactions. The combination of the two allows vision based interactions with the environment to be studied. The STTR is written to provide a framework allowing each of the component attributes of robotic simulation to exist in an integrated software suite and be improved over time so integrated robotics capabilities can be studied.</span>

Q6 (05/28/2020): For comparison, are there currently non open source products that come close to what you are describing here? If so can you list them?
A: <span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:#1F497D;
mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">There are commercial products that may offer simulation of multiple domains (sensing, vehicle dynamics, terramechanics, communications).&nbsp; However, it is unlikely that they will offer all the pertinent combinations of the simulation domains required by DoD researchers and their collaborators or the ability to make timely modifications based upon ongoing research. In addition it is expected that the simulator would work with other DoD robotics modular software based on ROS.&nbsp;&nbsp; A simulator that was working towards this use model was called ANVEL.&nbsp; ANVEL allowed models of military vehicles to be built and simulated in various environments. The vehicles could have tracks or wheels. The simulations could work in conjunction with real-time hardware in the loop simulators with Government and collaborator autonomous driving software.&nbsp;&nbsp; The environments could be quite extensive and have obstacles such as trees and buildings.&nbsp; There were some aspects of ANVEL that did need to be upgraded.&nbsp; Although the tire contact model was adequate, it did not model deformable terrain. ANVEL also did not model contact through manipulation well.&nbsp; ANVEL visualization was early gaming technology instead of modern photorealism so using it with vision based simulated sensors was not helpful in perception research.&nbsp; Although trees could be modeled in ANVEL, the simulated foliage could not be considered realistic as well.&nbsp; ANVEL did not keep up with advances in ROS and its interface with ROS architecture was quite limited. However when deficiencies arose ANVEL was able to be modified as needed for Government funded research and it did provide a means for collaboration and safe testing of software for full-scale platforms.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>

Q1 (06/10/2020): In Phase 2, the STTR states that performance should be evaluated "With materials supplied by the Government (three concretes, two rock types, and three soils) [...]". Does the government expect to provide further data, or are the performers expected to proceed with experiments using samples provided by the government?
A: <span style="font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif;
